<GuideLayout title="Qatar Labor Law Guide 2026: Essential Employee Rights" description="Essential Qatar labor law guide for 2026. Minimum wage QAR 1,000, working hours, leave, termination rules, and worker protections under reformed legislation. Updated for expats." canonical="/qatar/labor-law/" schemas={[buildBreadcrumbs(breadcrumbs), buildFAQSchema(faqs), buildArticleSchema("Qatar Labor Law Guide 2026: Essential Employee Rights", "Essential Qatar labor law guide for 2026.", "https://gulfexpathub.com/qatar/labor-law/", "2025-01-15", "2026-06-01")]} breadcrumbs={[{ name: "Home", url: "/" }, { name: "Qatar", url: "/qatar/guide/" }, { name: "Labor Law", url: "/qatar/labor-law/" }]}>
<h1>Qatar Labor Law Essentials 2026</h1>
<p>Qatar's labor law framework, based on Law No. 14 of 2004 and its subsequent amendments, has undergone the most significant reforms in the GCC region. The changes, implemented between 2020 and 2024, include the introduction of a non-discriminatory minimum wage, elimination of the kafala system, abolition of exit permits, and establishment of the Workers' Support and Insurance Fund. These reforms have fundamentally improved worker protections and modernized the employment relationship in Qatar.</p>
<h2>Minimum Wage</h2>
<p>Qatar was the first Gulf country to introduce a non-discriminatory minimum wage. Since March 2021, the minimum monthly basic wage is QAR 1,000, with additional minimums of QAR 300 for food and QAR 500 for accommodation if not provided by the employer. This applies to all workers regardless of nationality, sector, or employment type. The minimum wage is reviewed periodically and represents a floor for all employment contracts.</p>
<h2>Working Hours</h2>
<p>Standard working hours are 48 per week (8 hours per day, 6 days per week). During Ramadan, hours are reduced to 36 per week (6 hours per day) for Muslim employees. Overtime is paid at 125% of the basic hourly rate, with work on rest days and public holidays compensated at 150%. Summer outdoor work restrictions prohibit labor in direct sunlight between 10 AM and 3:30 PM from June 1 to September 15. Friday is the standard weekly rest day.</p>
<h2>Leave Entitlements</h2>
<p>Annual leave is a minimum of 3 weeks (21 days) after one year of service, increasing to 4 weeks (28 days) after 5 years. Sick leave is up to 2 weeks full pay, then 4 weeks half pay per year. Maternity leave is 50 days with full pay. Additional provisions exist for Hajj leave, marriage leave, and bereavement leave.</p>
<h2>Job Mobility and Contract Freedom</h2>
<p>Workers in Qatar can change employers without the previous employer's permission, provided they serve the notice period specified in their contract. The electronic contract system ensures transparency in employment terms. Workers can register complaints through MADLSA's labor dispute resolution system if employers obstruct the transfer process.</p>
<h2>End of Service</h2>
<p>End-of-service gratuity is a minimum of 3 weeks' basic salary per year of service. Employers may offer more generous terms contractually. See our <a href="/qatar/gratuity-calculator/">Qatar Gratuity Calculator</a> for detailed calculations.</p>
